{"key":"processedPost-9580100","value":{"id":9580100,"first":9535693,"last":9586112,"when":1231564436,"utime":"01/10/09 07:13 AM","cleanedPost":"I have no idea what you're trying to come up with.&nbsp; You don't use steam to humidify a growing chamber or it will all end up as condensation on the walls.&nbsp; You also don't want to heat a fruiting chamber for the same reason.&nbsp; That's why we use them in normal room temperature, so the fruiting chamber is already at the temp preferred by mushrooms.<br />You also don't want wet mist falling on your substrate trays or cakes.&nbsp; There must be evaporation of moisture from the substrate or fruiting performance is poor.&nbsp; This means you want your cakes to begin drying out, and then you mist.<br />Massive amounts of fresh air is one of the top pinning triggers, which at 99% humidity will cause the desired evaporation of moisture from the substrate.&nbsp; If you're growing in a tub, damp perlite in a shotgun terrarium will keep your humidity levels at the right spot for several weeks, which is more than enough for a cropping cycle.<br />If you're using a mini-greenhouse, go with coolmist humidfiers or you can go low-tech and hang a wet towel or two inside the greenhouse, and change it/them out every few days with fresh towels.<br />RR"}}